    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div id="pDiv" class="col-12">
                <h2>General:</h2>
                <p>
                    The main feature of Dice Chronicles is the strategic, gamble-based battles using dice. 
                    Each hero has their own unique set of 6 dice that's used for building combos and racking up damage.
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    Short version: 
                    <br>
                    Try to get combinations of dice you can see in the table (Under <a href="#eDiv">Example</a> below). Everything not resulting in "0" is a valid combination. You can roll as many times as you want, but you have to save at least one die after each throw. If you have a combination that gives 0 points at the end of your turn, you receive the rest of the damage you have accumulated yourself. 
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    Longer version: 
                    <br>
                    During your turn, you can roll as many times as you want, as long as you are able to store/save at least one die after each roll. 
                    If you manage to build a valid combo with all six dice, you may start over again, keeping and increasing your accumulated damage. 
                    You can also choose to roll the dice of a different hero in your team for the next round, trying to achieve <a href="/dice_battle_team_attacks"> team combos</a>
                    or maybe play a little safer. Theoretically, you can always accumulate enough damage to one-hit-KO your opponent, 
                    but going for it would be a huge gamble, as we will soon see. 
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    There are two ways in which your turn may end:<br>
                    1: You choose to end your turn<br>
                    <!-- 2: After your last roll (or rather after saving at least one die after your last roll), you are unable to (use all your saved dice in a valid combo.<br> -->
                    2: Your turn ends due to the effect of items or status conditions
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    If all your saved dice are part of a combo when your turn ends, you attack your opponent and deal the accumulated damage. 
                    If there are saved dice that are not part of a combo (a “stray die”), your opponent counterattacks, and you receive all the accumulated damage yourself. 
                    (Items and status conditions may affect this in different ways, but this is the main principle). 
                    <br>
                </p>
            </div>
            <!-- <div class="col-1"></div> -->
            <div id="eDiv" class="col-12">
                <h2>Example 1:</h2>
                <br>
                <img src="/images/MiasTable.png">
                <p>
                    This is Mias table. It's always available to look at if you need it. Again: Everything not resulting in 0 points is considered a valid "combo". For example three waves, one foot and one hand would result in 650 points and be considered valid. Two waves, three hands and two feet would not be valid, because two waves give 0 damage(You need three or more).
                </p>
                <img src="/images/MiasFirstRoll.png">
                <p>
                    Here is Mias first roll. The only "combo" we have now is one hand for 50 damage. That's too little if you ask me. I'd rather save the two waves and hope to get another one later. I can roll as many times as I want to as long as I store at least one die after each roll. For now, I'll only save the two waves. (The waterfalls also give 500 points, but the waves give my opponent a status condition earlier, as we can see from the table)
                </p>
                <img src="/images/MiasSecondRoll.png">
                <p>
                   Ops, scary... No wave here. Luckily, we have a foot which is always a valid combo (It never results in 0). We'll save that and hope for the best on our next roll.
                </p>
                <img src="/images/MiasThirdRoll.png">
                <p>
                    Wow! Talk about luck! Not only did we get wave that we needed - we also got more feet. Now, all our saved dice are valid, which means that we deal the accumulated damage to our opponent if we choose to end our turn (Reminder: You can always end tour turn after storing on die, no matter how many you have saved. You may end your turn with only one saved die if you want to!).
                </p>
                <img src="/images/MiasChoice.png">
                <p>
                    We can choose to end our turn here and deal 800 points to our opponent. Because we managed to use all our six dice, we can also roll all six again. We could for example roll with Sarah next, trying to give a second status condition and pull off a team attack. For now, let's just end our turn and get some damage on the board.
                </p>
                <!--<img src="/images/6.png">
                <p>
