                    As we can see from the table, we are unable to make a combo out of any of the remaining dice. 
                    Our combos failed, and we receive the 700 damage instead. Should have played it safe this time…
                </p>!-->
                <h2>Example 2:</h2>
                <br>
                <img src="/images/SimonsTable.png">
                <p>
                    This is Simons table. You can access the tables from the question mark to the right of the damage calculations.
                </p>
                <img src="/images/SimonsFirstRoll.png">
                <p>
                    This is Simons first roll. We got one tornado. Let's hope we can make that three in the following turns. We'll save it and roll again. I could also have saved the hand and foot, since they too are valid. If I did that though, I would have had fewer dice to get the rest of my tornados on. That is why I only take the one tornado from now. 
                </p>
                <img src="/images/SimonsSecondRoll.png">
                <p>
                   Ouch... No tornados and no hands nor feet to help us out. Our only options now are either to try for: 
                   <br>
                   - Straight
                   <br>
                   - Three pairs
                   <br>
                   - Three tornados and three of something else. 
                   <br>
                   If we save two "heavy wind" now, we have the opportunity to get either Three pairs or 3+3 later, so we'll do that. 
                </p>
                <img src="/images/SimonsThirdRoll.png">
                <p>
                   Okay, we got the tornado at least! Let's save that and roll again.
                </p>
                <img src="/images/SimonsFourthRoll.png">
                <p>
                   Okay, now we're in quite the predicament... 3 + 3 is off the table. We have to save the foot or the cloud, meaning there are not enough dice for both a tornado and "heavy wind". We could still try for Three pairs, though. Then it would be wise to save the cloud, because that gives 0 damage if it fails, while the foot gives 100. So we save the cloud.
                </p>
                <img src="/images/SimonsEnd.png">
                <p>
                    Okay, now what? Here, it comes down to our courage and luck. We have a 1/6 chance of getting the cloud we need. We have 2/6 chance of getting a third tornado or "heavy wind" which will make us lose 600 or 400 damage ourselves. (All accumulated damage are returned to us if we have any invalid combos in our saved dice). For now, let's just call it quits. If I were playing myself, I would definately have taken the risk and tried, but I wanted to take the opportunity to show how to tactically end your turn and minimize losses as well, if you are not a risk-lover like me.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
